America, Two Kinds of Citizens
New York—As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting ballots for the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the results are finally confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is expected in this fiercely contested, record-high voter turnout election.
Only U.S. citizens can vote for the U.S. president, but this choice affects people all around the world.
If it is too early to determine the election results now, it is not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
On the positive side, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite the practical restrictions related to the pandemic, voter turnout remains high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
The court is investigating a decision by the United States Postal Service, which appears to have been politically motivated, that hindered the delivery of ballots from regions where votes are expected to mainly come from the Democratic Party.
On Tuesday evening, the current U.S. president Trump declared victory without any basis, receiving almost no response, while his demand to stop the counting of votes (at least in the states where he is leading) seems to have been ignored.
However, it is worrying that the division among American voters remains significant.
The number of votes for the two candidates is almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democrats will win the White House and retain control of the House, while the Republicans will continue to control the Senate.
The governorships and state legislature seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republicans having a slight edge).
The Democrats' anticipated "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, probably securing around four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House.
This result did not come from strong authorization, nor did it arise from political adjustments.
Trump's polling numbers are very good, he received 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getting presidential candidate in American history, surpassing any previous winner.
Especially noteworthy is that this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily new coronavirus cases and over 1,000 deaths.
Just as the consequences of his government's poor handling of the pandemic became most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have significant influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems possible).
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant influence on the choice of the Republican nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of President Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern form of American populism — will still remain a powerful force.
It is no surprise that, despite having no evidence, Trump desperately tries to appear noble and upright, and attempts to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accuses of fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden as president.
Trump is very likely to never concede, and even less likely to attend the inauguration of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never met a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on shared views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civic curriculum provides convenience for the differentiation among people of different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that the differentiation of the country is mostly not divided along economic lines.
Voters from all social classes cast their votes for the two candidates, and the voting patterns in terms of population, gender, and race are not as one-sided as many people predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the remedies.
Education level is obviously an indicator of political orientation, and geographical location is also the case. Republican voters tend to live in suburbs and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to live in metropolitan areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be very important in elections, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Against this backdrop, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the way the president is elected or how the government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who will suffer losses due to change will resist the change.
This will make governance difficult.
This largely depends on the assessment of Mitch McConnell, the Republican leader of the Senate, and his ability and willingness to cooperate with the incoming President Biden.
Cooperation will also require Biden to make compromises, which will certainly be resisted by the more ideologically rigid members of his own party.
Democrats have tried to sharply reject everything Trump and his representatives stood for.
But they were not successful.
And Republicans were seeking an election that would gain Trump's approval.
But this also did not go as they wished.
On the contrary, the election revealed a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
